body:
An **exception** is an event that disrupts normal program flow. Java uses a structured exception-handling mechanism with `try`, `catch`, `finally`, and `throw`.

```java
try {
    // code that may throw
} catch (IOException e) {
    // handle specific exception
} catch (Exception e) {
    // handle any other exception
} finally {
    // always runs — cleanup code
}
```

Key rules:
- Catch more specific exceptions before more general ones
- `finally` runs even if an exception is thrown or a `return` is executed
- Multi-catch (Java 7+): `catch (IOException | SQLException e)`
- Don't swallow exceptions silently — at minimum log them
- Use `try-with-resources` for `AutoCloseable` resources

Exceptions propagate up the call stack until caught or the program terminates.

examples.code:
try {
    int result = 10 / 0;
} catch (ArithmeticException e) {
    System.out.println("Error: " + e.getMessage());
} finally {
    System.out.println("Always runs");
}

starterCode:
public class Main {
    static int divide(int a, int b) {
        // Throw an IllegalArgumentException if b is 0
        return a / b;
    }
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            System.out.println(divide(10, 2));
            System.out.println(divide(10, 0)); // should throw
        } catch (IllegalArgumentException e) {
            System.out.println("Caught: " + e.getMessage());
        } finally {
            System.out.println("Done");
        }
    }
}

examples.code:
// Checked — must handle
try {
    new java.io.FileReader("file.txt"); // throws IOException
} catch (java.io.IOException e) {
    System.out.println("File not found");
}

// Unchecked — no compile-time requirement
String s = null;
System.out.println(s.length()); // NullPointerException at runtime

starterCode:
import java.io.*;
public class Main {
    // Method with checked exception declaration
    static String readFirstLine(String path) throws IOException {
        try (BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new FileReader(path))) {
            return br.readLine();
        }
    }
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            String line = readFirstLine("nonexistent.txt");
            System.out.println(line);
        } catch (IOException e) {
            // Handle checked exception
            System.out.println("IO Error: " + e.getMessage());
        }
    }
}

body:
Custom exceptions make your error handling domain-specific and self-documenting. Create a custom exception by extending `Exception` (checked) or `RuntimeException` (unchecked).

```java
public class InsufficientFundsException extends RuntimeException {
    private final double amount;
    public InsufficientFundsException(double amount) {
        super("Insufficient funds: need " + amount);
        this.amount = amount;
    }
    public double getAmount() { return amount; }
}
```

Best practices:
- Include a meaningful message and any relevant context fields
- Provide multiple constructors (message, message+cause)
- Name it clearly: `UserNotFoundException`, not `NotFoundException`
- Prefer unchecked for programming errors; checked for recoverable conditions
- Always pass the original exception as a cause when wrapping

examples.code:
public class DataAccessException extends RuntimeException {
    public DataAccessException(String msg, Throwable cause) {
        super(msg, cause);
    }
}

try { /* DB operation */ }
catch (SQLException e) {
    throw new DataAccessException("Failed to load user", e);
}

