body:
**Exception chaining** (wrapping) preserves the original cause when re-throwing. This maintains the full diagnostic stack trace.

```java
try {
    // low-level operation
} catch (IOException e) {
    throw new ServiceException("Failed to load config", e); // e is the cause
}
```

The cause is accessible via:
- `e.getCause()` — the original exception
- `e.printStackTrace()` — shows the full chain

**Why it matters:** Without chaining, you lose the root cause. Catching `IOException` and throwing `new RuntimeException("error")` discards the original stack trace.

All `Throwable` constructors accept an optional `cause` parameter. Use `initCause()` when using a constructor that doesn't accept a cause.

examples.code:
class AppException extends RuntimeException {
    AppException(String msg, Throwable cause) { super(msg, cause); }
}

try {
    Integer.parseInt("not-a-number");
} catch (NumberFormatException e) {
    throw new AppException("Invalid config value", e);
}

starterCode:
public class Main {
    static class RepositoryException extends RuntimeException {
        RepositoryException(String msg, Throwable cause) { super(msg, cause); }
    }
    static void loadFromDB() {
        try {
            // Simulate a low-level failure
            throw new RuntimeException("Connection refused");
        } catch (RuntimeException e) {
            throw new RepositoryException("Cannot load user data", e);
        }
    }
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            loadFromDB();
        } catch (RepositoryException e) {
            System.out.println("High-level: " + e.getMessage());
            System.out.println("Cause: " + e.getCause().getMessage());
        }
    }
}

