public String readFile(String path) throws IOException {
    // throw actually throws the exception
    if (path == null) throw new IllegalArgumentException("Path is null");
    try (var r = new java.io.FileReader(path)) {
        return "content";
    }
}

starterCode:
import java.io.*;
public class Main {
    // Declare that this method may throw IOException
    static String readContent(String filename) throws IOException {
        if (filename == null || filename.isEmpty()) {
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Filename cannot be empty");
        }
        // Simulate reading — throw IOException for missing files
        throw new IOException("File not found: " + filename);
    }
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            readContent("");
        } catch (IllegalArgumentException e) {
            System.out.println("Validation: " + e.getMessage());
        } catch (IOException e) {
            System.out.println("IO: " + e.getMessage());
        }
    }
}

body:
**Try-with-resources** (Java 7+) automatically closes resources that implement `AutoCloseable` after the try block, even if an exception occurs.

```java
try (InputStream in = new FileInputStream("file.txt");
     BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader(in))) {
    String line = br.readLine();
} // in and br are automatically closed here
```

Benefits:
- Eliminates `finally { resource.close(); }` boilerplate
- Handles the case where both the try block and `close()` throw — suppressed exceptions are attached to the primary exception
- Resources are closed in reverse order of declaration

Any class implementing `AutoCloseable` (one method: `void close() throws Exception`) can be used. Java 9 allows using effectively-final variables declared outside the try block.

examples.code:
try (var br = new java.io.BufferedReader(new java.io.FileReader("file.txt"))) {
    String line;
    while ((line = br.readLine()) != null) {
        System.out.println(line);
    }
} catch (java.io.IOException e) {
    System.err.println("Error: " + e.getMessage());
}

starterCode:
public class Main {
    static class ManagedResource implements AutoCloseable {
        String name;
        ManagedResource(String name) {
            this.name = name;
            System.out.println(name + " opened");
        }
        public void close() {
            System.out.println(name + " closed");
        }
        void use() { System.out.println(name + " in use"); }
    }
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Use try-with-resources to open, use, and auto-close two resources
        // Observe the close order
    }
}
